          </style><script type="application/ld+json" id="page-json-ld-0" data-next-head="">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"NewsArticle","mainEntityOfPage":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/recipes/article/curried-cabbage-stew-toast-21270627.php","url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/recipes/article/curried-cabbage-stew-toast-21270627.php","headline":"Recipe: Curried Cabbage Stew with Turmeric-Chile Butter Toasts","articleSection":"Food/Recipes","publisher":{"@type":"NewsMediaOrganization","name":"San Francisco Chronicle","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","width":600,"height":60,"url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/sites/premiumsfgate/ldjson_logo.png"},"location":{"@type":"Place","name":"San Francisco Chronicle","address":{"@type":"PostalAddress","addressLocality":"San Francisco","addressRegion":"CA"}},"url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com","sameAs":["https://www.facebook.com/SFChronicle/","https://twitter.com/sfchronicle","https://www.instagram.com/sfchronicle/","https://www.linkedin.com/company/sfchronicle"]},"description":"This gently spiced cabbage, sweet potato and white bean stew hits the sweet spot between nourishing and indulgent, especially with turmeric-chile butter toast o","image":{"@type":"imageObject","width":2048,"height":1536,"url":"https://s.hdnux.com/photos/01/55/51/55/28744520/5/rawImage.jpg","thumbnailUrl":"https://s.hdnux.com/photos/01/55/51/55/28744520/5/square_small.jpg","caption":"Warmly spiced stew is paired with toast that’s slathered with seasoned butter. "},"articleBody":"There are some predictable cycles in the food media world. In the spring, everything on the plate must be green or have an egg involved. In the summer, it’s all about easy, fresh and staying away from the oven like it’s a bad idea. (The grill, however, is allowed.) Early fall is about getting back into a routine, whatever that means. Late fall through early winter turns cozy, sweet and very much about entertaining: what to bring, what to bake what will travel well. Winter is also about coziness, but it’s layered with this idea of new beginnings. Maybe that means pulling back on alcohol, easing off overly rich foods or just wanting something that feels grounding again. I used to think predictions like this were constraining, like they boxed us in. These days, I think it’s helpful to have loose guides and themes to help us decide what feels right to put on the table when the days are short and we’re cooking a little more by instinct. As for me, I keep coming back to balance. One night it’s pizza, the next it’s a big salad — sometimes it’s all on the same plate. With this week’s recipe, I’m firmly in the balance camp: a hearty vegetable stew paired with a big piece of butter-slathered toast. The stew is warmly spiced, which brings depth and comfort, but it’s softened by sweet potato, tender cabbage and creamy white beans. Savoy cabbage, if you can find it, is especially good here. It’s leafy, crinkly, and vibrantly hued. When it simmers, it turns tender without losing its structure. I think of it as a young vegetable with an old soul. Then there’s the toast. I prefer a thick piece of baguette, toasted in olive oil so it’s already rich before you even get to the butter. That butter is seasoned with earthy turmeric, bright lemon zest and crushed chile flakes for heat. It’s simple, but it does a lot. I highly recommend seasoning butter more often if you don’t already; it’s one of those small things that makes meals feel more intentional. In the end, this soup might be a predictable recipe for the beginning of a new year. Honestly, it’s exactly what I want right now. And hopefully, you do too. Curried Cabbage Stew with Turmeric-Chile Butter Toasts Serves 4 This winter meal pairs tender vegetables in a savory, gently spiced gingery broth with very rich toast. It feels soothing and revitalizing, but still indulgent enough to feel satisfying. If you can’t find Savoy cabbage (named for the Savoy region of France), green cabbage or Napa cabbage will work just fine. I suggest a curry powder that includes turmeric and garam masala, but if you have the individual spices and feel like mixing your own, I recommend it. The flavors will be brighter and more distinct. 3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil 2 cups diced sweet potato (from about 1 medium sweet potato) 1 medium yellow onion, diced small 4 large garlic cloves, thinly sliced  1-inch piece ginger, finely chopped  Salt and pepper 1 tablespoon curry powder 1 small head (about 10 ounces) of Savoy or green cabbage, cored and roughly chopped 6 cups chicken or vegetable stock  1 (14-ounce) can white beans, drained and rinsed 6 tablespoons unsalted butter, room temperature ¼ teaspoon turmeric ¼ teaspoon crushed red chile flakes  1 lemon 1 baguette, split in half lengthwise and toasted with olive oil  Cook the Curried Cabbage Stew: Heat the olive oil in a large size pot or Dutch oven over medium heat. Once the oil is warm, add the sweet potato, onion, garlic and ginger. Season with salt and pepper and stir. Cover with a lid and cook, lifting the lid to stir occasionally until the potato is fork tender and the onion is beginning to caramelize on the edges, about 8 to 12 minutes.  Stir the curry powder into the vegetables and follow with the cabbage. Season the cabbage with salt, then stir and cook it until it wilts to half its volume, about 3 minutes. Pour in the stock and bring to a simmer. Simmer until the cabbage has completely wilted and some white parts turn a bit yellow, about 7 minutes. Add the white beans and simmer for 1 more minute. Turn the heat off and season with salt to taste.   Make the Turmeric-Chile Butter: Meanwhile, add the butter, turmeric and chile to a small bowl and mix together with a fork. Finely grate in about half the lemon zest and season with salt.  Prepare the Toast: To serve, ladle the stew into bowls. Break the baguette into smaller pieces — I prefer large pieces, about ¼ of the total baguette — and toast. Spread the butter on the toast and place in the bowl with the stew. ","datePublished":"2026-01-09T12:00:00Z","dateModified":"2026-01-09T12:00:20Z","author":[{"@type":"Person","name":"Christian Reynoso"}],"isAccessibleForFree":false,"hasPart":{"@type":"WebPageElement","isAccessibleForFree":false,"cssSelector":".articleBody"},"inLanguage":"en"}</script><script type="application/ld+json" id="page-json-ld-1" data-next-head="">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"WebPage","breadcrumb":{"@type":"BreadcrumbList","itemListElement":[{"@type":"ListItem","position":"1","item":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.sfchronicle.com","url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com","name":"Home"}},{"@type":"ListItem","position":"2","item":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/","url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/","name":"Food"}},{"@type":"ListItem","position":"3","item":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/recipes/","url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/recipes/","name":"Recipes"}}]},"publisher":{"@type":"NewsMediaOrganization","name":"San Francisco Chronicle","url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/","address":{"@type":"PostalAddress","addressLocality":"San Francisco","addressRegion":"CA"},"logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.sfchronicle.com/sites/premiumsfgate/ldjson_logo.png","width":"600","height":"60"},"sameAs":["https://www.facebook.com/SFChronicle/","https://twitter.com/sfchronicle","https://www.instagram.com/sfchronicle/","https://www.linkedin.com/company/sfchronicle","https://bsky.app/profile/sfchronicle.com"]}}</script><script data-newrelic="true">window.NREUM||(NREUM={});NREUM.info = {"agent":"","beacon":"bam.nr-data.net","errorBeacon":"bam.nr-data.net","licenseKey":"NRJS-bef5859a29fb3c538c2","applicationID":"584873719","agentToken":null,"applicationTime":122.108411,"transactionName":"M11VbURXX0NXAUdbWgoXYFxUcENRWwdEXUcPbUVQGXhUSEIIQB1yIWwYFm0YHx5XDl9v","queueTime":0,"ttGuid":"6abb17b23a264673"}; (window.NREUM||(NREUM={})).init={privacy:{cook